# Wave 1 slot #15: Cloud Provider Integration (EKS).
# See testdata/e2e/vulnerable/15-cloud-eks.yaml for the workloads + aws-auth
# ConfigMap + IRSA-annotated SA that trigger these rules. The kind cluster is
# labeled eks.amazonaws.com/nodegroup by scripts/kind-e2e.sh so the
# collector's DetectCloudProvider classifies it as "eks". The assertions
# below run against .tmp/e2e-report-minimal so the aws-auth ConfigMap finding
# (anchored in kube-system) is not dropped by the standard exclusions preset.
KUBE-CLOUD-AWSAUTH-SYSTEM-MASTERS-001
KUBE-CLOUD-IRSA-ADMIN-ROLE-001
KUBE-CLOUD-IRSA-MISSING-001
KUBE-CLOUD-IMDS-PIVOT-001
KUBE-NETPOL-IMDS-001
KUBE-PRIVESC-PATH-AWS-IAM-ROLE

# KUBE-PRIVESC-PATH-SYSTEM-MASTERS also fires here via the cloud chain
# (ServiceAccount cloud-eks-test/eks-admin-irsa -> external aws-iam role ->
# system_masters sink), with the irsa_assume_role and aws_auth_admin hops
# visible in the EscalationPath array. The rule ID is already asserted by
# baseline.expect against the standard-preset scan, so we do not repeat it
# here.
#
# KUBE-PRIVESC-PATH-AWS-IAM-ROLE fires for the shorter "SA can assume this
# IAM role" chain that terminates at the external AWS IAM node itself. The
# pathfinder treats external IAM nodes as sinks (so they are captured) and
# continues traversal through them when they have aws-auth outbound edges,
# so the longer SA -> IRSA -> aws-auth -> system_masters chain also surfaces
# separately as KUBE-PRIVESC-PATH-SYSTEM-MASTERS.
